⁸⁸ 1 think that Bacon must here have in mind cosmical clouds, in the interstellar spaces, not ordinary or aerial clouds. The argument is thar the light of the stars, if it took a long time for its transmission‚ would be frequently stupped by various obstacles in the sky, whereas, on a clear night, we invariably see the stars where we expect to find them. At the same time, it must be confessed that, if there were such obstacles as 1 am l supposing Bacon to contemplate, the light might sometimes be intercepted, however instantaneous its transmission. There is, then, an undoubred difficulty in the passage, though it does not appear to me so great as it seems to appear to Mr. Spedding.
